The purveyors of politeness and civility have had it with the nation's unruly political candidates and the rude lot of journalits who egg them on.
Perhaps ``politics ain't beanbag,'' but we need some politeness in our politics, they say.
``It is the rules of etiquette that enable people to air controversy,'' Judith Martin, aka ``Miss Manners,'' told a Washington forum this week.
``The bigger the controversy the more rules you need.''
Meanwhile, an interfaith group has drawn up a list of ``thou shalt nots'' and persuaded a couple of dozen candidates to sign it.
